WEBVTT

00:06.648 --> 00:08.948
Says "Keep Out."
Don't mind that.

00:08.983 --> 00:11.618
What a cute little pond.

00:11.653 --> 00:13.786
I don't know about this, Brandy.
(scoffs)

00:13.820 --> 00:15.288
Can fish
really give pedicures?

00:15.322 --> 00:16.689
It's not like
they got hands.

00:16.723 --> 00:18.023
They don't need 'em.

00:18.057 --> 00:19.792
Fish just nibble off
the dead skin

00:19.826 --> 00:22.161
like a fat man
at an all-you-can-eat buffet.

00:22.195 --> 00:24.029
It's one of them
Japanese things.

00:24.063 --> 00:25.531
I read about it in a magazine.

00:25.565 --> 00:27.500
But what if it hurts?

00:27.534 --> 00:29.501
Hell, it ain't a beauty
treatment if it don't hurt some.

00:29.535 --> 00:33.004
Come on. Ladies up in New York
pay big bucks for this stuff.

00:33.038 --> 00:37.074
But you and me-- we're gonna
get it for free. Here.

00:37.109 --> 00:38.710
Try some of this.

00:38.744 --> 00:40.512
I swiped it from
Billy Ray's tackle box.

00:40.546 --> 00:42.580
Fish love
this stuff.

00:42.615 --> 00:45.417
Few minutes from now,
these busted ol' feet

00:45.451 --> 00:47.083
are gonna feel
soft as a baby's.

00:47.118 --> 00:49.853
Ooh.

00:49.887 --> 00:51.888
It kind of tickles,
don't it?

00:54.892 --> 00:56.360
"Hurts" is more like it.
Ow!

00:56.394 --> 00:58.529
One of these fish
got my entire foot in its mouth.

00:58.563 --> 01:00.130
Relax, drama queen.

01:00.164 --> 01:02.933
I'm serious, Brandy.
It really hurts.

01:02.967 --> 01:04.766
This is what I get for trying
to do something creative

01:04.802 --> 01:06.602
on ladies night. Next time,
we'll just stay at home...

01:06.637 --> 01:08.638
(both screaming)

01:11.642 --> 01:13.576
Get it off!
Get it off!

01:17.247 --> 01:19.716
BOOTH: <i>Look, I don't care what</i>
<i>your logbook says, okay?</i>

01:19.750 --> 01:24.018
But the package never got here,
delivered to my house.

01:24.053 --> 01:25.687
No, I don't
want to file a complaint.

01:25.722 --> 01:28.690
I just want my brother's ashes.

01:28.725 --> 01:31.360
Is there is a problem
with Jared's remains?

01:31.394 --> 01:32.961
Yeah, they're MIA.
Listen, do you...

01:32.995 --> 01:35.464
you haven't seen a box
around here, about this big?

01:35.498 --> 01:38.466
I-I would have noticed a box
of ashes from a crematorium.

01:38.500 --> 01:41.134
Don't worry, Booth.
We'll track it down.

01:41.169 --> 01:42.970
I couldn't help Jared
when he was alive,

01:43.004 --> 01:44.672
now I can't even find his ashes.

01:44.706 --> 01:48.075
Mommy, Daddy,
Can I wake up Hank now?

01:48.109 --> 01:50.578
Christine, what did we say
about waking a sleeping baby?

01:50.612 --> 01:52.913
But he wants me to get in his
crib and read him a story.

01:52.947 --> 01:54.814
Oh, okay,
I'll tell you what.

01:54.849 --> 01:56.683
Okay, when I'm done here looking
around for what I'm trying

01:56.717 --> 01:58.048
to find, I'll come
read you a book, okay?

01:58.072 --> 01:59.499
What are you
looking for, Daddy?

01:59.500 --> 02:01.121
Oh. Daddy's
looking for Uncle Jared.

02:01.154 --> 02:03.189
No, no.
But Daddy said Uncle Jared

02:03.223 --> 02:05.291
was in Heaven.
No, uh,

02:05.325 --> 02:08.026
Uncle Jared was cremated.
Daddy's looking for his ashes.

02:08.061 --> 02:10.363
Really, do we have to explain
something like that to her?

02:10.398 --> 02:12.364
Do you have to do that?
Death isn't something

02:12.399 --> 02:13.932
to be shied away from, Booth.

02:13.966 --> 02:15.534
From an anthropological
standpoint,

02:15.568 --> 02:17.369
the more openly
a culture

02:17.404 --> 02:20.972
embraces death, the less anxiety
they associate with it.

02:21.007 --> 02:23.108
(phone rings)
A body was found

02:23.142 --> 02:24.943
at a fish farm in West Virginia.
It's being brought

02:24.977 --> 02:26.945
to the Jeffersonian.
Listen, all right,

02:26.979 --> 02:28.323
I'll tell you what-- go-go
get dressed, monkey.

02:28.423 --> 02:30.782
But what about reading to Hank?
I'll tell you what,

02:30.816 --> 02:32.316
I'll do it tonight,
okay? But today

02:32.350 --> 02:34.519
is Mommy and Daddy's
first day back at work.

02:34.553 --> 02:36.020
Go, go, go, go get
dressed, okay?

02:43.495 --> 02:44.962
Hey, hey, welcome back!

02:44.996 --> 02:46.630
Hey, thanks, good
to see you, man.

02:46.664 --> 02:48.197
So, listen, listen, I
talked to the divers, okay?

02:48.232 --> 02:49.380
They went through the pond.

02:49.404 --> 02:50.756
There's no sign
of weapons or I.D.

02:50.757 --> 02:52.202
Whoa, whoa, you don't
need to jump right in.

02:52.236 --> 02:54.203
I know you've been through a lot...
Talking about?

02:54.238 --> 02:56.873
It's great to be here. We're
back. I'm going back to work!

02:56.908 --> 02:58.207
Huh?
Hey, hey, listen, Booth, before you go in...

02:58.242 --> 03:00.410
Okay.

03:00.445 --> 03:04.246
BOOTH:
Whoa. Wow. What happened here?

03:04.280 --> 03:07.450
You do remember retiring, right?

03:07.484 --> 03:09.452
Yeah, I just,
that, uh... this...

03:09.486 --> 03:11.286
this has been my office
for years.

03:11.321 --> 03:13.989
HR said they'd
find you something amazing.

03:14.023 --> 03:15.624
You know, if it's a problem,
we can, uh...

03:15.659 --> 03:16.959
No, no problem.

03:16.993 --> 03:19.527
Okay? I'm fine, I'm good.

03:19.562 --> 03:21.362
No problem at all.

03:21.396 --> 03:24.532
This is good for a fresh
start. Look at these, huh?

03:24.567 --> 03:27.301
Moving up in the
world, huh, pal?

03:27.336 --> 03:30.371
Yeah, you know,
I even got my own mini fridge.

03:30.405 --> 03:32.373
You got a mini fridge? Okay,
let's get back to work.

03:32.407 --> 03:34.308
Yeah. (clears throat)
Right, okay, sorry.

03:34.343 --> 03:36.810
So I was thinking--
a fish farm

03:36.845 --> 03:39.045
is a pretty unique place
for a body dump. Plus,

03:39.080 --> 03:41.482
not everyone knows that
trout are carnivorous.

03:41.516 --> 03:44.317
Farm there's out in the boonies,
so whoever dumped the body

03:44.352 --> 03:46.820
definitely knew of the location.
I'll check out their log books,

03:46.855 --> 03:49.155
see if we can figure out
who's been coming and going.

03:49.190 --> 03:50.357
Yeah, you should do that.

03:56.730 --> 03:58.698
So, Dr. Brennan, is being back
at the Jeffersonian

03:58.732 --> 03:59.999
just like riding a bike?

04:00.033 --> 04:03.002
Uh, conducting
a forensic examination

04:03.036 --> 04:05.838
bears no resemblance
to riding a bicycle.

04:05.873 --> 04:08.140
Though both are activities
I greatly enjoy.

04:08.174 --> 04:11.309
Well... would you
like to do the honors?

04:11.343 --> 04:13.444
Oh, yes! Please.

04:16.616 --> 04:20.519
I really have missed this.
(giggles)

04:22.955 --> 04:25.123
(laughs)

04:26.692 --> 04:29.827
Okay. All right,
lower it.

04:29.861 --> 04:31.328
Okay.

04:31.362 --> 04:33.130
BRENNAN:
I talked to Booth.

04:33.164 --> 04:35.699
Based on the drag marks
at the site,

04:35.734 --> 04:38.536
he thinks the victim
was transported

04:38.570 --> 04:40.771
to the pond for disposal.

04:40.805 --> 04:42.472
Booth's back at work today, too?
Yes.

04:42.507 --> 04:44.774
His brother's death
was traumatic,

04:44.808 --> 04:48.711
but a routine can be healing
in times of stress.

04:48.746 --> 04:52.481
Uh, speaking of,
how is Arastoo's job search?

04:52.516 --> 04:55.618
I wouldn't know.

04:55.653 --> 04:57.787
Arastoo and I
are taking a break.

04:57.821 --> 05:01.157
Oh. I'm sorry to hear that.

05:01.191 --> 05:02.390
I hope my return

05:02.425 --> 05:05.360
to the Jeffersonian
was not a factor.

05:08.464 --> 05:11.800
You coming back is what
the Jeffersonian needed.

05:13.369 --> 05:15.971
The prominent
supra-orbital ridge

05:16.005 --> 05:18.073
suggests the victim
was male.

05:18.107 --> 05:19.807
And the wear
on the mandibular teeth

05:19.841 --> 05:21.809
indicates he was in his 40s.

05:21.843 --> 05:22.910
BRENNAN:
There's a great deal of damage

05:22.945 --> 05:23.911
to the mandible.

05:23.946 --> 05:25.913
It appears to be perimortem.

05:25.948 --> 05:28.315
Uh, same with the fractures
to the right tibia and fibula.

05:28.349 --> 05:30.250
Perhaps they were caused
by the same implement?

05:30.285 --> 05:32.086
But we won't be certain

05:32.120 --> 05:34.655
until we recover the missing
pieces of the mandible.

05:34.690 --> 05:38.424
Fish predation to the organs
and flesh is extensive.

05:38.459 --> 05:40.159
HODGINS:
That is because

05:40.194 --> 05:41.595
<i>Oncorhynchus Mykiss--</i>

05:41.629 --> 05:42.963
otherwise known
as rainbow trout--

05:42.997 --> 05:44.631
are total carnivores.

05:44.665 --> 05:46.766
And this variety
was bred to eat fast

05:46.801 --> 05:48.134
and grow fast.

05:48.168 --> 05:49.970
They are perfect
for fish farming.

05:50.004 --> 05:52.005
So, why are they here?

05:52.039 --> 05:54.439
Well, these little fellas
were actually feeding

05:54.474 --> 05:55.975
on the victim
when he was hauled out.

05:56.009 --> 05:57.810
BRENNAN:
Dr. Hodgins,

05:57.844 --> 06:00.479
are you positing that
the missing mandible fragments

06:00.513 --> 06:03.115
are inside those fish?

06:03.149 --> 06:04.416
That's my theory.

06:04.450 --> 06:07.419
And I intend to retrieve them

06:07.453 --> 06:09.121
by any means necessary.

06:12.120 --> 06:16.120
